Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat
#oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @Yukon Gold Potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on one side of
a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of oil, @Fry Seasoning{1%tablespoon},
@salt{}, and @pepper{}. (For 4, spread potatoes out across entire sheet.)

Roast on top rack for ~{10%minutes} (you'll add the green beans then).

Meanwhile, zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

In a #shallow dish{}, combine @Panko Breadcrumbs{1/2%cup},
@lemon zest{}, and @Garlic Powder{1%teaspoon}. Season with @salt{1%tsp} (we used
1 tsp; 2 tsp for 4 servings) and @pepper{}; set aside.

Pat @Chicken Cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; place between 2 large
pieces of @plastic wrap{}. Pound with a #mallet{} or #rolling pin{} until chicken
is about ½ inch thick. Season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> If your cutlets are already ½ inch thick, skip the pounding.

Once potatoes have roasted 10 minutes, remove sheet from oven. Carefully toss
@Green Beans{6%ounce} on empty side with a drizzle of oil, @salt{}, and
@pepper{}. (For 4 servings, leave potatoes roasting and toss green beans on a
second sheet; roast on middle rack.)

Return to top rack until veggies are browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes} more.

Meanwhile, brush chicken all over with half the @Sour Cream{4%tablespoon} (you'll
use the rest in the next step). Working one piece at a time, press chicken into
panko mixture to coat on both sides.

Heat 1⁄3-inch layer of @Cooking Oil{2%teaspoon} in a large, #heavy-bottomed pan{}
over medium-high heat. Once oil is shimmering and hot enough that a pinch of
panko mixture sizzles when added to the pan, add chicken and cook until crust is
golden brown and chicken is cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

Transfer to a paper-towel-lined #plate{}.

While chicken cooks, in a #small bowl{}, combine @Honey Dijon Dressing{1.5%ounce}
with remaining sour cream.

Divide chicken, green beans, and potato wedges between plates. Drizzle chicken
with as much sauce as you like (save a bit for dipping if desired). Serve with
any remaining sauce and lemon wedges on the side.